==== Step G1: IDO/TDO activation (synthesis failure)

*Probes:* Same as kynurenine cascade Step H1. LDN reduces IDO induction; 1-MT inhibits IDO directly; anti-inflammatory combination suppresses multiple IDO-inducing pathways. The distinction in THIS cascade: NAD⁺ synthesis failure vs. serotonin depletion. Both result from the same IDO activation but have different drug targets.

*If LDN restores NAD⁺ levels (measurable in serum/whole blood):* TLR4-mediated IDO induction is the dominant mechanism of NAD⁺ depletion — LDN reduces IDO → restores tryptophan availability for NAD⁺ synthesis. This should be correlated with kynurenine/tryptophan ratio.

*If LDN does NOT restore NAD⁺ but NMN/NR DOES:* NAD⁺ depletion is from tryptophan diversion (LDN reduces IDO but NAD⁺ synthesis capacity from tryptophan is permanently impaired due to enzyme deficiencies in the kynurenine→NAD⁺ pathway — 3-hydroxyanthranilate 3-4-dioxygenase or quinolinate phosphoribosyltransferase deficiency). NMN/NR bypasses the de novo pathway entirely by providing the salvage pathway substrate directly.
